Title: SHELF LIFE
Credit: written by
Author: Joshua Brooks
Draft date: First Draft
Notes: Three timelines, cut against each other -- 1989, THE YEAR, and AFTER. The audience assembles the chronology themselves. No scene sits in pure sincerity longer than it can stand. Nobody in this film ever says what it is about.
Contact: --

/* STRUCTURE NOTE: Three strands. "1989" -- Dale and Cass as kids, where the fear got installed. "THE YEAR" -- spring to winter, Cass's illness. "AFTER" -- Dale and Nora, unlabeled at first, so that early audiences don't know for certain what it means. That uncertainty is doing story work. Do not clarify it in the first act. */

FADE IN:

INT. DALE'S KITCHEN -- HIGH DESERT, CALIFORNIA -- MORNING [AFTER]

A kitchen organized like a submarine galley. Labeled canisters in rows. A wall-mounted radio. A laminated card by the stove: SHUT-OFF VALVE LOCATIONS.

DALE HARMON, 47, broad, careful, a man built like a load-bearing wall, is making a school lunch with a VACUUM SEALER.

He seals a peanut butter sandwich into a plastic brick. Sets it beside: a sealed brick of carrot sticks, a sealed brick of Goldfish crackers, and an emergency mylar blanket folded to the size of a playing card.

NORA, 9, backpack on, watches from the doorway with the flat patience of a child who has chosen her battles.

NORA
The other kids' sandwiches aren't in bricks.

DALE
The other kids' sandwiches are stale by ten a.m.

NORA
Marisol's mom uses a Ziploc.

DALE
(sealing the juice box -- the juice box -- into plastic)
A Ziploc isn't rated for anything.

NORA
It's rated for sandwiches.

Dale considers this. Slides the sealed bricks into her lunchbox, which has a carabiner on it, and a whistle.

DALE
Emergency blanket stays in the bottom. You don't have to use it. It just lives there.

NORA
(taking the lunchbox; heading for the door; over her shoulder, deadly)
Marisol asked if my family was in the army and I said no, my uncle is just like this.

The door bangs. Dale stands in the galley kitchen, alone, holding the vacuum sealer.

He looks at it.

DALE
(to the sealer)
A Ziploc isn't rated for anything.

CUT TO:

INT. LUZ CAFE -- BAKERSFIELD -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

SUPER: "SPRING"

A strip-mall Mexican diner. Formica, sugar packets, a TV playing daytime court shows on mute. CASS HARMON, 43 -- Dale's sister, wiry, quick, the fast-talking one to his slow one, a hospital cafeteria hairnet pushed up on her head like a tiara -- sits across from Dale in a booth. Two menudos. She hasn't touched hers.

CASS
Okay so don't do the thing.

DALE
What thing.

CASS
The thing you do. Where I say something and your face doesn't move and then you go home and buy four hundred dollars of tarps.

DALE
That was one time, and the tarps were on clearance --

CASS
Dale.

Something in her voice. He stops. The court show plays silently over her shoulder: someone being awarded damages.

CASS (CONT'D)
They found a thing. On the scan. It's in the pancreas, which -- I already looked it up, don't look it up, the internet is a horror movie --
(she rotates her coffee cup a quarter turn; her tell; he knows it and we will learn it)
They're saying months. Plural, which is nice. Nobody would commit to a number of months, so I've decided it's a lot. I've decided it's like, forty months.

A long silence. Dale's face doesn't move.

CASS (CONT'D)
You're doing the thing.

DALE
I'm not doing the thing.

CASS
Your face is a parking lot, Dale. Say words.

DALE
(and his first words, after his sister says she is dying, are:)
Which hospital? Because Kern Medical's generators are twenty years old, I've seen the specs, if there's a grid event mid-treatment --

CASS
(putting her hand flat on the table; not angry; this is the reaction she expected, planned around, maybe even needed)
There it is.

DALE
Cass --

CASS
No -- it's fine. It's you. You heard "dying" and you went straight to the generators.
(she finally picks up her spoon; eats a bite of menudo, because her body still gets hungry, which offends her)
Everybody else is going to cry on me for six months. You're going to inspect generators.
(beat)
Honestly? I picked the right person to tell first.

INT. HARMON HOUSE -- KITCHEN -- NIGHT [1989]

SUPER: "1989"

A different kitchen -- avocado appliances, a wall phone with a long tangled cord. YOUNG DALE, 11, husky, serious, stands on a chair at the counter with a flashlight, a box of saltines, a can of soup, and a whistle, arranging them in a shoebox with terrible precision.

YOUNG CASS, 7, gap-toothed, watches from the table, coloring.

YOUNG CASS
What's it for?

YOUNG DALE
It's a kit.

YOUNG CASS
What's a kit?

YOUNG DALE
It's for if something happens.

Down the hall, through a door ajar: a bedroom lamp, and the sound of their MOTHER coughing -- long, wet, wrong, the cough of a thirty-eight-year-old woman with something nobody has named in front of the children yet.

Young Dale stops arranging. Listens until the cough ends. Then keeps arranging.

YOUNG CASS
(coloring; not looking up)
Is something gonna happen?

YOUNG DALE
(aligning the whistle parallel to the flashlight)
Not if there's a kit.

The logic of an eleven-year-old, laid out in a shoebox: if you prepare for the thing, the thing can't happen. The film will spend two hours dismantling this sentence.

INT. DALE'S HOUSE -- GARAGE -- NIGHT [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

The garage does not contain a car. It contains STEEL SHELVING to the ceiling: water barrels, ammo cans of documents, buckets labeled in Dale's block handwriting -- RICE 2041, BEANS 2039, LASAGNA (25 YR) -- rows of them, a supermarket for a customer base of one.

Dale, home from the diner, stands in the middle of it. Jacket still on. Keys still in his hand.

He stands there a long time.

Then he takes a legal pad off a shelf, sits on a bucket of beans, and begins to write. We see the heading:

INSERT -- LEGAL PAD: "CASS -- CONTINGENCIES." Below it, a numbered list already growing: "1. Second opinion (UCLA? Stanford?) 2. Transport redundancy -- if truck down, backup vehicle 3. Generator specs Kern Med 4. Freezer meals -- 90 day rotation 5."

He stops at 5. The pen hovers.

Number 5 is the one that has no words. He writes nothing. He goes back and underlines "Freezer meals" twice.

This is a man calming himself, and it looks exactly like a man planning a rescue, and the film would like you to notice that from here on you cannot tell those two things apart. Neither can he.

INT. NORA'S SCHOOL -- PICKUP LINE -- DAY [AFTER]

Dale's pickup truck idles in a line of crossover SUVs like a bear at a dog park. Nora climbs in, drops her backpack in the footwell.

NORA
We're doing family trees. I need photos.

DALE
(pulling out, checking mirrors twice)
Of who?

NORA
Family. That's the tree part.
(beat; looking out the window; the too-casual voice of a nine-year-old handling explosives)
Ms. Okafor said I can do the tree "however feels right." She said it in the voice. Everybody knows the voice.

Dale drives. His jaw works once.

DALE
We got photos. There's a whole ammo can of photos.

NORA
Our family pictures are in an ammo can.

DALE
It's waterproof, fireproof, and it stacks.

NORA
(looking out the window; quietly; not a complaint, just data)
Marisol's are in an album shaped like a heart.

DALE
(beat; changing lanes with enormous care)
Ziploc people.

INT. KERN MEDICAL -- ONCOLOGY -- CONSULT ROOM -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

Cass on the exam table in a paper gown she wears like a heckler. Dale in the corner chair with the legal pad. DR. VUONG, 40s, kind, precise, has clearly met a thousand families and never one shaped quite like this.

DR. VUONG
-- so with this staging, the honest conversation is about time and quality of time. There are treatment paths, and we'll talk about all of them, but I don't want to sell you a --

DALE
(from the corner; reading off the pad)
What's the hospital's generator capacity?

DR. VUONG
I'm -- sorry?

DALE
Backup power. If she's mid-infusion and the grid fails. It's a heat wave grid out here, it fails every August. What's the switchover time?

DR. VUONG
(genuinely trying)
I... believe there are redundant systems --

DALE
"Believe" or know?

CASS
(to Dr. Vuong; pleasant; jerking a thumb at Dale)
He's not insane, he's just like this. Keep going, doctor. If the power goes out he'll be delighted, he's got a truck full of extension cords.

DR. VUONG
(recalibrating; continuing)
The first decision point is whether we pursue the aggressive protocol --

And as she talks, the film stays on DALE, in the corner, writing everything down in block letters, filling the page, flipping it, filling the next -- a man taking dictation from a landslide. His notes are perfect. His hands are perfect. He is not okay, and the notes are how you can tell, and only one person in the room can read that language.

Cass, from the table, watches her brother write.

She lets him.

INT. HARMON HOUSE -- HALLWAY -- NIGHT [1989]

Young Dale, in pajamas, stands outside his mother's cracked bedroom door with the SHOEBOX KIT under his arm. Listens. No coughing right now. Just the TV inside, low.

He sets the kit down on the hallway floor, square against the door frame. Aligns it with the base board.

MOTHER (O.S.)
(from inside; warm, tired, amused)
Dale Robert Harmon. Is that another kit?

YOUNG DALE
(caught; to the door)
It's for you. There's a whistle. If something happens and I'm at school, you blow it and Mrs. Petrakis next door --

MOTHER (O.S.)
Come in here.

Young Dale opens the door partway. We stay in the hall. We never enter this room, the whole film. Through the gap: lamplight, a shape in the bed, and a hand -- thin, freckled -- reaching out to take the shoebox from him, and holding his wrist for a second along with it.

MOTHER (O.S.) (CONT'D)
It's a good kit.
(beat)
Where's yours?

YOUNG DALE
(pause)
Mine?

MOTHER (O.S.)
You make everybody a kit, baby. Where's yours?

Silence in the hallway. Young Dale looks at his own hands like they belong to the school lost-and-found. He has no answer. He will not have an answer for thirty-six years.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. HIGH DESERT SURPLUS & SUPPLY -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

A warehouse store for the worried: gun safes, water filtration, buckets of the future. Dale pushes a flatbed cart. Beside him, riding the end of the cart like a kid, because she is dying and store rules have stopped applying to her: CASS, in a beanie now -- round one of chemo has started collecting its fees.

CASS
(reading a bucket label)
"Chicken -- la King. Serves twelve. Shelf life: twenty-five years."
(to Dale)
Who is the customer for this? Who's throwing a dinner party for twelve in the apocalypse?

DALE
It's not servings, it's calories. You buy calories.

CASS
I'm just saying, -- la King is ambitious. The world ends and this bucket's like, "tonight -- a cream sauce."

A store EMPLOYEE, 20s, in a tactical vest that has never known danger beyond restocking, approaches.

EMPLOYEE
You folks finding everything? We got a promotion on the two-year med kits --

CASS
(bright)
Do you have anything for pancreatic cancer?

The employee's mouth opens. Stalls. Closes.

EMPLOYEE
...We have iodine tablets?

CASS
(nodding; grave)
Close.

The employee retreats. Dale gives Cass a look. Cass gives it right back, twice as hard.

CASS (CONT'D)
What? Everybody gets to be scared of the end of the world in here except me?

DALE
(pushing the cart; low)
You're not the end of the world.

CASS
(riding the cart; looking down the aisle of buckets; quieter, and for once not joking fast enough to beat the sincerity)
I'm the end of one.

The cart rolls past the buckets. Twenty-five-year lasagna. Thirty-year oats. All this food for afters. Dale doesn't answer. He puts a water filter on the cart that nobody asked for.

INT. CASS'S APARTMENT -- KITCHEN -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

A regular human kitchen: bills on the counter, a kid's drawing on the fridge -- crayon family: CASS, NORA, and a large rectangle-shaped man labeled "UNCLE DAIL." Dale unloads groceries. Real ones -- produce, milk. His versions of flowers.

Nora, at the table, does homework with the specific loudness of a child listening to everything.

CASS
(putting away milk; conversational; setting the trap gently)
Saturday, you're taking us somewhere.

DALE
Where?

CASS
Your bunker.

Dale stops, a can of soup in each hand.

DALE
It's not a bunker. It's a reinforced --

CASS
Dale. I've known about it for six years. Denny told Linda, Linda's a talker. You bought the old pistachio farm and you put something under it.
(closing the fridge; facing him)
Saturday. Full tour. Nora brings a juice box, we make a day of it.

DALE
Why?

CASS
(and she holds his eyes just one second too long before she puts the smile back on)
Because I want to see where all your money went, and because you can't say no to me anymore. It's the one good coupon this disease comes with, and I am CLIPPING it.

NORA
(from the table; not looking up)
What's a bunker?

CASS
It's a basement with self-esteem, baby. Do your math.

EXT. PISTACHIO FARM -- HIGH DESERT -- SATURDAY -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SPRING]

Dead trees in rows, a rusted water tank, a shipping container that isn't just a shipping container. Dale unlocks three locks. A steel staircase descends into cool dark.

INT. THE BUNKER -- CONTINUOUS

Lights hum on. And it's -- honestly -- kind of magnificent. A buried world: bunk room, kitchen shelf-wall, a rack of radios, an air system breathing softly. Everything labeled. Everything level. Ten years of a man's Sundays and most of his salary, arranged against the dark.

Nora runs in like it's a playground, immediately touching things.

NORA
Is this a SECRET? Are we in a SECRET?

DALE
Filtration's there. Water's gravity-fed from the tank. Power's solar with a hand-crank backup. Air scrubber's rated for --

CASS
(walking slow, touching a shelf edge, reading labels)
Rice, 2041. Beans, 2039.
(she stops; something on the shelf catching her)
Dale.

She's looking at a section of shelving -- newer wood, different screws. Recently built. On it: kid-sized boots, a smaller sleeping bag, a bin labeled "N -- CLOTHES, SIZES 10-16." Sizes she hasn't grown into yet. A shelf for the future of a child, running years deep, like the rice.

Cass reads the label. Reads her daughter's future measured out in bin sizes. Her hand goes to her mouth for one second --

NORA (O.S.)
(from the bunk room; a shriek of joy)
THERE'S A HAMMOCK!

-- and the moment is punctured, on schedule, and Cass laughs instead of the other thing, wet-eyed, and Dale pretends to check a gauge.

CASS
(quietly; not looking at him; at the bin labels)
When did you build this part?

DALE
(checking the gauge; which does not need checking)
Spring.

The word does its work. Spring. The diner. The menudo. He came home from learning she was dying and he built shelves for her daughter.

Cass nods slowly. Rotates an imaginary coffee cup a quarter turn.

CASS
Sit down, Dale.

DALE
The air system --

CASS
The air system's fine. Everything in here is fine. It's the finest room in Kern County. Sit.

He sits on a bunk. She sits across from him on a bucket of beans -- rhymes with the garage, and she doesn't know that, but the movie does. Somewhere off, Nora swings in the hammock, singing something tuneless.

CASS (CONT'D)
Robbie's out. You know Robbie's out. He sends the checks and the birthday texts and that's the whole man, that's all the man there is.
(beat)
Mom's gone. Dad's -- wherever Dad is. Phoenix. Whatever.
(beat; here it comes; she says it the way you'd hand someone a live wire)
It has to be you.

Silence. The air system breathes.

DALE
(very quietly)
Cass, I vacuum-seal sandwiches.

CASS
I know.

DALE
I own four hundred pounds of rice and no album shaped like a heart. I've never -- I don't know what she needs. I know what she'd need if the grid fails. Nobody's ever needed what I have, Cass. That's the -- 
(and he stops, because he has never said the next sentence out loud, and he doesn't say it now either. He looks at the shelf wall instead. All of it. 2039. 2041.)

CASS
(watching him; gently; the scene's turn)
You built a room under the ground with sixteen years of her clothes in it, Dale.
(beat)
You think I'm asking because there's nobody else. I'm asking because when I told you I was dying, everybody else said "anything you need." You went home and I know for a fact you sat in that garage and started a list with my name on it.
(beat)
Show me the list.

DALE
(pause)
No.

CASS
Because it's forty pages?

DALE
(pause)
It's sixty pages.

CASS
(closing her eyes; a smile breaking through like a leak)
Sixty pages.
(she leans forward, takes his hand off his knee, holds it on top of the live wire)
That's the whole job, you giant idiot. That's all parenting is. It's a sixty-page list you never finish, for a person you can't protect, forever. You've been in training your whole stupid life.

Off in the bunk room, the hammock creaks. Nora, upside down in it now, hair hanging:

NORA
(calling)
Can we live here?!

CASS
(calling back; eyes still on Dale)
No, baby. It's for emergencies.

NORA (O.S.)
What emergency?

Cass looks at Dale. Dale looks at Cass. Neither answers the child.

The air system breathes for everyone.

INT. KERN MEDICAL -- INFUSION CENTER -- DAY [THE YEAR -- SUMMER]

SUPER: "SUMMER"

Recliners in rows. IV poles. Cass in a chair, line in her arm, beanie on. Dale beside her in a hard chair with a cooler he packed at 5 AM.

He unpacks it, item by item, onto her tray table: sealed brick of crackers. Sealed ginger chews. A thermos labeled BROTH. A backup thermos labeled BROTH 2.

CASS
(watching the procession)
What's in Broth 2?

DALE
Broth.

CASS
What was wrong with Broth 1?

DALE
Nothing's wrong with Broth 1. Broth 2 is if Broth 1 --

CASS
(to the NURSE passing by, gesturing at Dale)
He has a backup broth.
(to Dale)
You know the other families bring, like, a magazine?

DALE
(arranging the ginger chews at a reachable angle; gruff; this is the closest he can get to saying it and they both know it's exactly as close as he can get)
Ziploc people.

Cass laughs -- and the laugh catches on the chemo nausea, and turns into a long, bad moment, eyes shut, riding a wave. Dale doesn't flinch. He's already there, basin in one hand -- from the cooler, of course there's a basin in the cooler -- other hand steady between her shoulder blades. Not rubbing. Just present. A load-bearing hand.

The wave passes. She breathes.

CASS
(eyes still closed; hoarse; quiet)
Okay. The broth thing's less funny now.

DALE
(uncapping Broth 1; pouring)
It was never funny. It's a protein delivery system.

CASS
(taking the cup with both hands; small)
It's a little funny.

Around them, the infusion center hums -- a room full of recliners, every one its own version of this scene, every visitor's bag its own kind of kit. The film lets us see the whole row for a moment: the husband with the crossword he isn't doing, the daughter with the phone she isn't reading. Everybody scared. Everybody caretaking. Same posture.

INT. HARMON HOUSE -- LIVING ROOM -- DAY [1989]

The front door stands open to hard daylight. A DUFFEL BAG waits by it.

THE FATHER, 40, jeans and a windbreaker, crouches to Young Dale's height. Young Cass is on the stairs, watching through the banister rails like a small prisoner.

FATHER
(low; man-to-man; the worst speech ever given)
You're the guy now, okay? Look after your mom. Look after Cassie. You're good at that stuff -- you're like me, you're practical.
(he taps Dale's chest, once, like installing something)
You're the guy.

He picks up the duffel and goes down the walk. He doesn't look back, but he does adjust the bag strap twice, the fidget of a man outrunning his own exit.

Young Dale stands in the doorway. Eleven years old. Newly appointed.

Behind him, from the stairs:

YOUNG CASS
(matter-of-fact; seven)
Is he coming back?

YOUNG DALE
(watching the car pull out; and here's the boy building the man in one line, block letters, laminated)
Doesn't matter. We have a kit.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. DALE'S HOUSE -- NORA'S ROOM -- NIGHT [AFTER]

A kid's room mid-colonization: half moving boxes, half installed life. A reading lamp. Glow stars on the ceiling in astronomically incorrect positions that someone was not permitted to correct.

Dale, laundry basket under one arm, opens the closet to put away folded clothes -- and stops.

On the closet floor, tucked behind the shoe rack: a BACKPACK. Not her school one. Packed hard, zippers straining.

He shouldn't. He does.

Inside: a flashlight. Two vacuum-sealed sandwich bricks, stolen from his own kitchen. A rolled t-shirt. Four granola bars. A juice box. A whistle -- her lunchbox whistle, transferred. And a folded piece of paper, crayon on it: the family drawing off Cass's old fridge -- CASS, NORA, UNCLE DAIL -- creased into eighths, protected in the middle of everything, like documents.

A go-bag. A nine-year-old's go-bag.

Dale sits down slowly on the edge of her bed with the backpack on his knees, and the film stays on his face while a man watches his own childhood arrive by return mail. It is the exact kit from 1989 -- his kit, reinvented independently, two generations of scared children packing calories against the dark.

The bathroom door opens down the hall -- water running, Nora's off-key humming. Dale moves fast: repacks it exactly -- sandwich bricks, bars, whistle, drawing folded back into eighths -- zips it, sets it behind the shoe rack at its original angle.

Nora pads in, toothpaste-breathed, and climbs into bed. Dale is innocently holding laundry.

NORA
You're doing the statue thing in my room.

DALE
Putting away clothes.

NORA
(getting under the covers; watching him with Cass's exact eyes)
Okay.

He turns off the big light. Pauses at the door.

DALE
(not looking at the closet; carefully, into the dark)
You know if anything ever -- if there's ever a problem, any kind. You come get me. That's the whole plan. I'm the plan.

NORA
(already half-asleep; devastating in the way only the half-asleep can manage)
I know. You're the plan.
(beat)
I have a backup plan.

Dale stands in the doorway a long moment.

DALE
(quietly)
Yeah. Okay.

He pulls the door to. In the hallway, alone, he leans his back against the wall next to her door -- the exact geometry of a hallway from 1989 -- and stays there a while, on watch, guarding against nothing that can be guarded against.

INT. CASS'S APARTMENT -- LIVING ROOM -- DAY [THE YEAR -- FALL]

SUPER: "FALL"

The apartment has grown medical equipment the way rooms do -- a hospital bed where the couch angle used to be, an oxygen concentrator chugging in the corner like a patient aquarium. Cass, smaller now, sharper-boned, holds court from the bed with a legal pad OF HER OWN.

Dale is installing a grab bar in the hallway. Drill in hand. Third grab bar today.

CASS
(reading from her pad)
Item one. The funeral. No slideshow. I mean it, Dale, if there's a slideshow set to acoustic music I will haunt you specifically --

DALE
(from the hallway; drilling)
No slideshow.

CASS
Item two. Nora keeps her last name. Robbie will not surface about this but if he surfaces --

DALE
He won't surface.

CASS
Item three.
(beat; and her voice changes gear, and the drill stops)
The school has a counselor, her name's Ms. Okafor, she's good, Nora likes her, the file's already open. Tuesdays. You keep the Tuesdays, Dale. Whatever else falls apart, the Tuesdays are load-bearing.

Dale comes to the doorway, drill still in hand, dust on his forearms.

DALE
(gruff)
You're making a list.

CASS
I'm making YOUR list. Sixty pages. I'm starting it for you.
(she pats the bed; he doesn't move; she pats it again, harder, and he comes and sits, drill and all)
Item four.

She sets the pad down. Item four isn't on the pad.

CASS (CONT'D)
When it happens -- and we're past "if," we're deep into "when," the doctors have stopped doing the weather-report voice --
(beat)
-- you're going to want to build something. That week. I know you. You'll want to pour a foundation. Buy a decade of something.

DALE
(looking at the drill in his hands)
Cass --

CASS
Let me finish, I rehearsed this.
(beat)
Build if you have to. Buy the buckets. I'm not going to fix you from a hospital bed, that's arrogant.
(she takes his wrist -- the same grip as a freckled hand through a door in 1989, and the film trusts us to feel the rhyme without a flashback)
But every bucket you buy, you look at it once and you ask it one question. Out loud. I want you to promise the out-loud part, because in your head you cheat.

DALE
What question?

CASS
"Is this for her -- or is this for it?"
(beat)
Her, you keep. It -- the fear, the whole roaring thing you've been feeding since you were eleven -- it doesn't get my daughter. It got you. It's not getting her.

A long silence. The oxygen concentrator chugs. Dale looks at his sister -- at the pad, at the bed rails he installed, at the grab bars marching down the hallway, at everything he has built between her and the dark, none of it working, all of it necessary.

DALE
(the most words he's said at once in the whole film, and every one costs a dollar)
When Mom was sick I made her a kit. Saltines and a whistle. I figured -- if the kit's there, the thing can't happen. That was the deal I made. Nobody signed it but me.
(beat)
The thing happened anyway. And I remember standing in the hallway thinking: the kit was wrong. Not the deal -- the KIT. Wrong crackers. Something. So I got better at kits.
(beat; he looks at her; forty-seven years old and eleven)
I'm still doing it. I know I'm still doing it. I got a room under a pistachio farm that can keep two hundred people alive for a year, Cass, and I can't --

He stops. The sentence arrives at the wall it has been driving toward his whole life.

CASS
(softly; finishing it because someone finally has to)
-- and you can't keep me.

The words land in the room and just sit there, true.

CASS (CONT'D)
(beat; and then, because no moment in this family is allowed to sit in sincerity longer than it can stand)
Two hundred people? Who ARE these people? You don't LIKE two hundred people. You like maybe four people. Three. It's three, Dale.

DALE
(wiping his eyes with the back of the drill hand; rough; grateful for the exit)
It's a calorie calculation.

CASS
You built Noah's Ark for a man with three friends.

DALE
(standing; back to the grab bar; voice not quite steady)
Item five. What's item five.

CASS
(picking the pad back up; and her voice isn't quite steady either, and neither of them mentions it, which is how this family says everything)
Item five. Teach her to drive when it's time. On the truck. Nobody learns anything on a Prius.

INT. CASS'S APARTMENT -- KITCHEN -- NIGHT [THE YEAR -- WINTER]

SUPER: "WINTER"

The kitchen, late. Dale cooks -- actually cooks, real food, a pot of something careful -- while filling labeled deli containers in rows on every counter. Dozens of them. TUES LUNCH. WEDS DINNER. The masking-tape genealogy of love in this family.

Through the doorway, in the living room: Nora, in pajamas, is curled on the hospital bed next to Cass -- both asleep, television still going, a cooking-show blue washing over them. Cass's arm is around her daughter. On the bedside table, Cass's legal pad, pages of it filled now.

Dale comes to the doorway with the wooden spoon in his hand. Looks at them a long time.

Then he goes back into the kitchen and keeps filling containers, quietly, so quietly, the ladle touched to each rim so it doesn't ring against the plastic. A man in an apron building a seawall out of soup, one pint at a time, all night if the pot holds out.

The film holds the doorway between the two rooms -- the sleeping and the cooking, the dying and the preparing -- in the same frame.

/* NOTE: We never see her death. This is the last scene of THE YEAR strand. The next time we see the apartment, it is being packed into boxes. The audience will do the arithmetic in the cut, the way this family would want it done: privately, off-screen, with the labels facing out. */

INT. CASS'S APARTMENT -- DAY [AFTER -- THE BEGINNING OF AFTER]

Boxes. The hospital bed is gone -- a rectangle of unfaded carpet where it stood, the exact ghost-geometry of the plaque dust and the bench screw holes of other stories, and of this one.

Dale wraps dishes in newspaper, alone. Slow. Nothing efficient about him today, first time in the film.

He opens the freezer to empty it -- and stops.

The freezer is FULL. His containers. TUES LUNCH. WEDS DINNER. Weeks of them, untouched, going back into fall. She stopped being able to eat long before she told him. She let him keep cooking anyway.

Dale stands in the cold breath of the open freezer, reading masking-tape labels in his own block handwriting, understanding -- all at once, the way these things arrive -- that the meals were never a protein delivery system. She'd known that from the first container. She let him fill her freezer for the same reason a mother once let a boy leave a shoebox at her door.

Because the kit was never for the person it was labeled for.

Dale closes the freezer. Rests his forehead against it. One breath. Two.

From the doorway:

NORA (O.S.)
Uncle Dale?

He straightens. Turns. Nora, 9, in the doorway of her own emptied home, backpack on both shoulders. The backpack.

NORA (CONT'D)
Which car do I go in?

And that's the whole custody arrangement, the whole future, the whole third act, in five words from a kid in a doorway.

DALE
(steady; because for her he can be; that's the discovery of his life happening in real time)
Mine.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. DALE'S HOUSE -- HALLWAY / NORA'S ROOM -- 2:14 AM [AFTER]

Dark. A small sound wakes the house -- a whimper, a cough. Dale is in the hallway in eleven seconds, a man who has clearly slept dressed for years.

Nora, in bed, flushed, glassy, miserable.

NORA
(small)
I don't feel good.

Dale's hand goes to her forehead. Hot. Genuinely hot.

And watch him: the machine spins up. This -- THIS -- he has trained for. He is gone and back in forty seconds with a medical kit the size of carry-on luggage. Thermometer -- the good one, the temporal artery one. 102.8.

DALE
Okay. Okay.
(opening the kit; ampules, instruments, a suture set, a POCKET GUIDE TO AUSTERE MEDICINE)
Okay.

He looks at the kit. The kit contains: a tourniquet. Water purification. Israeli battle dressings. QuikClot. Burn gel. Fish antibiotics, three kinds.

The kit does not contain: children's Tylenol.

Dale stares into the carry-on-sized hole in his life's preparation. Fourteen thousand dollars of readiness, rated for gunshot wounds and grid collapse, and the emergency is 102.8 in a nine-year-old, and the answer is a purple syrup sold at every gas station in America, and he doesn't have it.

NORA
(from the pillow; watching him stare into the bag)
Do I need the tourniquet?

DALE
(closing the bag)
No.

NORA
(closing her eyes; even at 102.8 the timing is her mother's)
This is a bad kit.

INT. 24-HOUR PHARMACY -- BAKERSFIELD -- 2:51 AM

Fluorescent purgatory. Dale moves down the children's aisle like a man defusing it, phone in hand, on with the NIGHT NURSE LINE.

DALE
(into phone)
-- 102.8 temporal, re-checked twice, onset roughly ninety minutes ago, no rash, lungs clear, she's -- 
(beat)
-- I put my ear on her back. I don't own a stethoscope.
(beat; quieter; the admission of the entire film)
I own everything else.

NIGHT NURSE (V.O.)
(kind; been doing this thirty years)
Sir, it sounds like a fever. Kids get them. Alternate acetaminophen and ibuprofen, fluids, call your pediatrician in the morning. She's going to be fine.

DALE
(standing in the aisle, a bottle of purple syrup in each hand, not moving)
"Fine."

NIGHT NURSE (V.O.)
Fine. This is the most normal call I'll get tonight.

Dale looks at the purple bottles. Something lets go in his shoulders -- not relief exactly. Scale. The emergency is small. The emergency was always going to be small. Emergencies mostly are, and they come anyway, purple syrup and Tuesdays, and no bunker has a shelf for them.

DALE
(into phone; gruff)
What's the dosage by weight? She's sixty-one pounds.

NIGHT NURSE (V.O.)
It's on the box, hon.

DALE
I'd rather hear it from a person.

A pause on the line. Thirty years of night calls, and something in that sentence lands with her anyway.

NIGHT NURSE (V.O.)
(gentler)
Yeah, okay. Got a pen?

DALE
(already writing on his palm in block letters)
Go.

INT. DALE'S HOUSE -- NORA'S ROOM -- 3:40 AM

Nora, dosed, sweaty, asleep. The fever doing its ordinary work. Dale sits on the floor beside her bed, back against the nightstand, a cup of the purple syrup's little dosage cup on his knee like a shot glass.

He's not on his phone. Not reading a manual. Just sitting. On watch. The one supply he's always had in surplus.

His eyes drift to the closet. The shoe rack. The go-bag behind it.

A long moment. Then, moving quietly, he pulls the go-bag out, opens it, and -- item by item -- unpacks it. Sandwich bricks back to the kitchen pile. Granola bars to the pantry pile. He works gently, repacking her fear into household shelves where it can just be food again.

At the bottom: the whistle, and the folded crayon drawing. CASS, NORA, UNCLE DAIL.

The whistle he holds a long time.

He doesn't take it. He puts the whistle back in the empty bag, alone, with the drawing -- and leaves the bag where it was, behind the shoe rack. Lighter by everything except the two things that were never supplies.

Some kits you don't confiscate. You just quietly cancel the emergency they were packed for, one Tuesday at a time.

INT. NORA'S SCHOOL -- COUNSELOR'S OFFICE -- DAY [AFTER]

MS. OKAFOR, 50s, cardigan, unhurried eyes, sits across a small table from Dale, who occupies the child-adjacent chair like a bear at a tea party. Between them: Nora's FAMILY TREE project.

It is not a tree. It is a diagram of the BUNKER -- cross-section, crayon, meticulous -- and in the bunk room, three figures: NORA, UNCLE DAIL, and above them, not in the bunker but drawn into the dirt and grass OVER it, arms out flat like a superhero mid-flight, or like someone lying on a lawn looking up: MOM.

MS. OKAFOR
She presented it to the class. I want you to hear how she explained it, because I think you should have it word for word.
(reading from a sticky note, carefully)
"My mom doesn't fit inside anymore, so she's the ground. The ground is how the bunker stays a bunker. It holds the roof on."

Dale looks at the drawing for a very long time. The crayon woman in the earth, arms out, holding the roof on.

MS. OKAFOR (CONT'D)
Tuesdays are working, Mr. Harmon. I wanted you to know. Whatever you're doing at home --

DALE
(still looking at the drawing; hoarse)
I'm mostly just there.

MS. OKAFOR
(nodding; sliding the drawing across the table for him to keep; the professional summary of the entire movie, delivered mildly, between appointments)
That's the active ingredient. Everything else is packaging.

INT. HARMON HOUSE -- KITCHEN -- NIGHT [1989 -- FINAL FRAGMENT]

The avocado kitchen, one last time. Later that year -- winter light, a casserole dish on the counter from some neighbor, the house in the hushed aftermath the film has never shown and doesn't now.

Young Dale, in a clip-on tie, sits at the table. In front of him: the SHOEBOX KIT, returned to him, the way hospitals return belongings. The saltines. The flashlight. The whistle.

Young Cass, 7, in a stiff dress, climbs onto the chair beside him. Looks at the box. Looks at her brother's face, which is a parking lot.

She takes the whistle out of the box. Turns it over. And then -- seven years old, in a funeral dress, in the quietest house in California -- she blows it. Loud. Shrill. Absurd. A referee calling a foul on the universe.

Young Dale stares at her.

She blows it again, right at him, cheeks out, defiant, until -- there -- the corner of his mouth. She hands him the whistle. He looks at it.

He blows it. Tentative. Then really. Then they're BOTH doing it, trading it, blasting this stupid whistle in their funeral clothes in the empty kitchen, two orphaned kids sounding an alarm about everything, until it collapses into the kind of laughing that is also the other thing.

The whistle was never for Mrs. Petrakis next door. It was never for emergencies.

It was so somebody would come. And somebody did. They came for each other, whistle-first, for the next thirty-six years.

INT. DALE'S KITCHEN -- EVENING [AFTER -- WINTER]

SUPER: "TUESDAY"

The galley kitchen, softened by months: a kid's drawing taped over the SHUT-OFF VALVE card. A heart-shaped photo album on the counter, half-filled, next to the ammo can it's slowly emptying.

On the table, steaming in a casserole dish: dinner. Nora eyes it.

NORA
What is it?

DALE
Lasagna.

NORA
From where?

DALE
(beat)
The garage.

NORA
(fork frozen)
The BUCKET lasagna? The twenty-five-year lasagna?

DALE
Twenty-five-year SHELF LIFE. It's four years old. It's basically new.

NORA
Why are we eating the apocalypse food? Is something happening?

And Dale sets down the serving spoon, and answers her honestly, which is the entire distance this man has traveled:

DALE
No. Nothing's happening.
(beat)
That's the occasion.

Nora considers this -- considers him -- and takes a bite. Chews. The verdict assembles.

NORA
(chewing)
...It's not terrible.

DALE
High praise.

NORA
It's like regular lasagna that's scared of you.

Dale barks a laugh -- an actual laugh, ambushed out of him, the first of the film -- and Nora grins at having caused it, and they eat the emergency, one fork at a time, on a Tuesday, for no reason, which is the best reason.

On the counter, faintly ridiculous in the domestic light: the vacuum sealer. Unplugged. There's a Ziploc box next to it.

EXT. PISTACHIO FARM -- HIGH DESERT -- DAY [AFTER -- SPRING]

SUPER: "SPRING"

One year since a diner booth in Bakersfield. The dead orchard, the shipping container, the whole buried kingdom -- and on the grass above it, exactly where a crayon drawing put a flying woman: a PICNIC BLANKET.

Dale and Nora eat sandwiches on it. Regular sandwiches. In Ziplocs.

NORA
(looking at the container door)
Do we still have it? Everything under there?

DALE
We still have it.

NORA
Good.
(lying back on the blanket, hands behind her head, her mother's exact gesture on her mother's exact ground)
But we don't have to go in.

DALE
(lying back too; to the sky)
No. We don't have to go in.

Wind through dead pistachio rows. Somewhere below them, sixteen years of shelves keep their long, patient vigil, rated for everything except what actually happens, guarding a boy's old promise in the cool dark. Let them. Some things you don't dismantle. You just move the picnic upstairs.

Nora fishes in her jacket pocket. Comes out with the WHISTLE. She's had it all along.

She blows it -- one short, bright, pointless blast across the empty orchard. A referee calling a foul on the universe. A kid making a noise because she can.

She hands it to Dale.

He looks at it. Thirty-six years of alarm.

He blows it. Long. Loud. For absolutely no one, about absolutely nothing, needed by nobody --

-- which is, at last, the whole point.

The sound carries out over the orchard and the desert takes it, easily, the way it takes everything, and the two of them lie back on the ground that holds the roof on.

FADE OUT.

THE END

/* FINAL NOTE: The word is never said. If any character, in any draft, ever observes that "care" is hiding inside "scare," cut the line and salt the earth where it stood. The audience gets to find it in the parking lot. That's their whistle. */